# Check for Existing Utilities First

Before writing any non-trivial logic inline in a component, **search `frontend/lib/` for existing utilities**.

## Key Libraries

| File | Provides |
|------|----------|
| `frontend/lib/csv-utils.ts` | CSV parsing (RFC-compliant, handles quoted fields), column role auto-detection (`guessRole`), date normalization, debit/credit mapping, `buildMappedRows`, `buildBulkMappedRows`, fuzzy category matching (`matchCategories`, Levenshtein distance) |
| `frontend/lib/api.ts` | All API calls, type exports (`BulkImportPayload`, `ImportProgressEvent`, `ImportCompleteEvent`), streaming NDJSON helper |

## Rules

1. **Never write an inline CSV parser** -- use `parseCsv` from `csv-utils.ts`.
2. **Never hardcode column name lookups** -- use `guessRole` and `buildMappedRows`/`buildBulkMappedRows`.
3. **Never write inline date parsing** -- use `normalizeDate` from `csv-utils.ts`.
4. **Never write inline category matching** -- use `matchCategories` from `csv-utils.ts`.
5. If a utility doesn't exist yet, create it in `frontend/lib/` with tests, then import it.

## Why This Matters

The CSV import dialogs were rewritten with a naive 3-line CSV parser that split on commas (breaking on quoted fields) and hardcoded column names, while `csv-utils.ts` (298 lines, 51 tests) sat unused on disk.

## Updating This Rule

When creating a new shared utility in `frontend/lib/`, add it to the Key Libraries table above so future work discovers it.
